(303, 2, '2014-08-15 01:36:40', '2014-08-15 01:36:40', 'It’s obvious that generating revenue through sales is what keeps a business running. With a subscription based business, capturing early product sales and managing risks to retain those customers have an important role in generating futures sales.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<strong>How can you accelerate early sales and retain customers?</strong>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nIt starts with introducing your solution in an appropriate way and engaging trusted, local influencers to build credibility.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nWe have a framework of <strong>5 Customer Funnels</strong> you can use to follow the customer through their product journey and ideas on how you can bring them along each step of the way (Figure 1).\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<strong>5 Customer Funnels</strong>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Acquisition</strong> – People come to your site after they’ve heard about you through email, press, blogs, word of mouth, and other paid or unpaid channels.</li>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n	<li><strong>Activation</strong> – If people like what they see on the landing page, email invitation, app store or other form of advertising they’ll become users by creating an account and beginning   their free trial.</li>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n	<li><strong>Retention</strong> – Users come back to the app through unsolicited use, emails reminders or push notifications and stay active through features they encounter while using the product.</li>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n	<li><strong>Revenue</strong> – You monetize active users through paid subscriptions.</li>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n	<li><strong>Referral</strong> – Active users refer others through viral product features and other incentives.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<a href="/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/figure_1.png"><img src="/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/figure_1-300x159.png" alt="figure_1" width="300" height="159" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-302" /></a>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nFigure 1\r\n&nbsp;\r\nLet’s take a deeper dive into each of these.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<strong>Acquisition &amp; Activation</strong>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThis is all about getting customers interested in what you have to offer (acquisition) and getting them to begin the trial (activation). Prior to actually acquiring customers, you’ll want to answer some questions to help refine messaging for the product.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nTo begin, let’s define the value proposition – the primary reason a customer should buy from you.  Once defined, this is first thing visitors should see on the landing page and all major entry points.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nAnswers (from people who could become real customers) on a few basic questions can help to determine the language of your customer and further define your value proposition.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>How can I save or acquire more time/money/information using this product?</li>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n	<li>How can improve my perceived worth/quality in front of my clients/peers?</li>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n	<li>How can I feel personally rewarded?</li>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n</ol>\r\nExamples of product features/benefits and opportunities from these 3 questions include the following:\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>How can I save or acquire more time/money/information using this product?</strong>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nPre-choreographed music and workouts saves you time.\r\n\r\nLess expensive than DVD’s\r\n\r\nAccess content only available here\r\n\r\nTeach classes anywhere\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<strong>How can improve my perceived worth/quality in front of my clients/peers?</strong>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nContent updated regularly to keep classes fresh\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<strong>How can I feel personally rewarded?</strong>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nEarly access to events\r\n\r\nExclusive offers/promotions\r\n&nbsp;\r\nOn your product landing page then, the value proposition is usually a block of text (a headline, sub-headline and one paragraph of text) with a visual (photo, hero shot, graphics).\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThere is no one right way to go about it, but I suggest you start with the following formula:\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Headline. What is the end-benefit you’re offering, in 1 short sentence.  An attention grabber.</li>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n	<li>Sub-headline or a 2-3 sentence paragraph. A specific explanation of what you do/offer, for whom and why is it useful.</li>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n	<li>3 bullet points. List the key benefits or features.</li>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n	<li>Visual. Images communicate much faster than words. Show the product, the hero shot or an image reinforcing your main message.</li>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Solve their objections</strong>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nNext, make it easy for them to begin. Supporting value add-copy can help reduce reasons a customer may not purchase or begin a trial.  Examples include:\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Free trial</li>&nbsp;\r\n	<li>Monthly to Month agreement, cancel any time</li>&nbsp;\r\n	<li>Money-back guarantee</li>&nbsp;\r\n	<li>Limited time discount</li>&nbsp;\r\n</ul>\r\nDemonstrating the actual, tangible solution is often the best way to introduce something new. Every new solution can benefit from a well-designed demonstration. The free trial along with a video tutorial or other interactive content helps show which aspects of your solution pose the biggest perceived risk to your customer.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nOn top of this, other marketing activities to consider include the following:\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Landing page optimization\r\n<ul>&nbsp;\r\n	<li>Making the product simple to purchase and easy to try before they buy.</li>\r\n	<li>Creating a remarkable customer experience through design and content.</li>\r\n	<li>Creating a separate product landing page to accurately track and manage.</li>\r\n	<li>Site A/B Testing to optimize copy and design.</li>\r\n</ul>&nbsp;\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Email\r\n<ul>&nbsp;\r\n	<li>Testing email campaigns to optimize conversion</li>\r\n	<li>Evaluating open, click thru and conversion rates</li>\r\n	<li>Auto-responder if cart abandonment</li>\r\n	<li>Automate remarketing</li>\r\n</ul>&nbsp;\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>SEO\r\n<ul>&nbsp;\r\n	<li>Capture interested potential customers</li>\r\n</ul>&nbsp;\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Content Marketing\r\n<ul>&nbsp;\r\n	<li>Leveraging blog posts, infographics, and videos to increase awareness and site traffic</li>\r\n</ul>&nbsp;\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Paid Acquisition\r\n<ul>&nbsp;\r\n	<li>Search engine marketing (Google AdWords; Facebook ads; display ads; mobile ads).</li>\r\n</ul>&nbsp;\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNext, establish credibility by aligning customer influencers. Who do your customers listen to in the your industry?&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Get their early buy-in, familiarization with the product and recognize them for their importance to the company.</li>\r\n	<li>Selective extended trials (a full year) exchange for testimonials. Capture written and video testimonials about the benefits of the program</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n	<li>Social Media\r\n<ul>&nbsp;\r\n	<li>Have a coordinated/scripted social medial messaging and cadence developed for their use.</li>\r\n</ul>&nbsp;\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Retention:</strong>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThe number one goal is to have customer retention. Successfully solving a customer’s problem and continuing to engage them enables a long-standing relationship to develop.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nEngagement is built into the product, as this is a critical component to long-term program success.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nSome goals with retention are to maintain the buzz and excitement of the product and deepen the connection with the community of subscribers.&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Live conversations\r\n<ul>&nbsp;\r\n	<li>Speaking with a small number of active customers and those who cancelled.  Provides great feedback about what is working well and more importantly what needs to be improved.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Surveys\r\n<ul>&nbsp;\r\n	<li>Use tools including Survey Monkey and Net Promoter Score (a good leading indicator of other metrics) to measure their willingness to refer the product and affinity for existing or proposed features.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Email/Push</li>\r\n</ul>&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Auto-responder emails are built into our platform based on user interaction with the app.</li>\r\n	<li>Push notifications with content updates and encourage social sharing</li>\r\n	<li>Exclusive member newsletter or email communication and promotions.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Revenue:</strong>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nWith a simple monthly subscription and reasonable rates there’s not much do here.  If you are having issues with retention it’s either a product or pricing problem.\r\n\r\nCommunicating with customers is a sure way to find our what they want from the product.\r\n\r\n<strong>Referral:</strong>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nWith any great solution, this will happen naturally, but probably not as quickly as you would like. It is important to look for points where you can influence the natural process to accelerate widespread adoption and to provide easy ways for people to talk and share about the program.&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Building buzz: recommendations &amp; referrals</li>\r\n	<li>Encourage users to share through social media</li>\r\n	<li>Sales reps and industry partners</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Where to begin</strong>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nIt’s impossible to focus your efforts on each of these steps at the same time.  Choose one of the five funnels and focus relentlessly on improving, then reassess and begin again. We recommend a 5 Step process for considerations when planning your efforts.&nbsp;\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Prioritize the plan. What are the 1 or 2 metrics we want to improve?</li>\r\n	<li>List our intent. Why do we want to change?</li>\r\n	<li>List the customer friction to solve. What’s the user experience problem?</li>\r\n	<li>Determine baseline conversion. What is the current status?</li>\r\n	<li>Consider potential lift from test. How much do we expect to gain?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nAs an example, let’s assume we are in the acquisition phase and we’ve already emailed an invitation to begin the free trial to a portion of the potential customer list.  We’ve noticed the open rates of the email are lower than expected.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nGoing through the 5 Steps is as follows:&nbsp;\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>We want to improve email open rates</li>\r\n	<li>To increase the number of people who have the opportunity to begin a free trial</li>\r\n	<li>They aren’t finding the subject line compelling enough to open</li>\r\n	<li>Current open rates are 20%</li>\r\n	<li>Expect a 10% lift with a change to the subject line</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nOr, another example would be this:&nbsp;\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>We want to improve the number of site visits to the app landing page from people not on our mailing list.</li>\r\n	<li>To increase the number of people who have the opportunity to experience our brand and begin a free trial</li>\r\n	<li>People outside of our permission marketing channels aren’t aware of what the app</li>\r\n	<li>Current organic site visits account for 5% of traffic</li>\r\n	<li>Request our current users to rate the app in the app store will improve the app ranking and increase organic site visits to 7.5% within 45 days.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nWhile having a great product is the most important success factor, a methodical and persistent approach to optimizing the customer funnels will further accelerate sales.', 'Simple Framework to Accelerate Revenue', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '300-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-08-15 01:36:40', '2014-08-15 01:36:40', '', 300, 'http://staging.classcast.co/300-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
