(376, 3, '2014-09-07 09:24:41', '2014-09-07 09:24:41', '<p style="color: #4b5c66;"><strong>SYDNEY, 1 September 2014</strong> – Premier health, fitness and wellness provider Classcast (www.classcast.co), founded by two passionate fitness technology advocates, has today announced the availability of a completely redesigned service, providing a faster, simpler and more effective content publishing experience.</p>\r\n<p style="color: #4b5c66;">In conjunction, the company released their new website and brand. "At Classcast we continue to improve the relationship with our customers. Our brand is an integral part of this communication and the website is key in establishing this message.  We''re excited to see this phase, and look forward to showing the industry more in the future," says Stuart Guest-Smith, CEO of Classcast.</p>\r\n<p style="color: #4b5c66;">This is the next step in the companies journey Aidan Green, Head of Product Design at Classcast, stated it is imperative to ensure that we provide the best tools and services for our customers; and design is something at the heart of Classcast''s culture.</p>\r\n<p style="color: #4b5c66;">“With the new Classcast, we’ve gone even further, making it simpler, faster and more visually effective to create an experience that''s unique to our industry," said Green. "We decided to specialize on the health, fitness and wellness industry, for that reason our product is built to support the range of amazing content creators out there."</p>\r\n<strong>About Classcast</strong>\r\n<p style="color: #4b5c66;">Classcast is the groundbreaking content publishing platform for the health, wellness and fitness industry that is reinventing the way people discover, deliver and create content. Start earning monthly recurring revenue for your content, connect directly to your customers, and deliver content anywhere anytime - to any mobile.</p>\r\n<p style="color: #4b5c66;">For businesses all over the world - fitness professionals, therapists, educators, life coaches, rehab specialists, physiotherapists... and many more in our amazing industry!</p>\r\n<p style="color: #4b5c66;">Launched in October 2014, Classcast is headquartered in San Francisco and was founded by Stuart Guest-Smith and Suren Reddy. Join 1000'' of happy and growing customers today! For more information and to sign up, visit <a title="Classcast Website" href="http://www.classcast.oc">www.classcast.co.</a></p>\r\n <span style="color: #4b5c66;">Follow us @twitter.com/classcastapp</span>', 'Classcast Introduces Fresh Coat of Paint with Revamped Design', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '360-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-09-07 09:24:41', '2014-09-07 09:24:41', '', 360, 'http://www.classcast.co/360-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(377, 2, '2014-09-07 09:36:23', '2014-09-07 09:36:23', '<strong>State of DVD’s vs Digital</strong>\r\n\r\nThe <a href="http://degonline.org">Digital Entertainment Group</a> reports physical disc sales have fallen over 30% since their 2004 peak. While the demand for content is on the rise, more people want content distributed to them through their mobile device.\r\n\r\nShifting to a monthly subscription model for content distribution enables you to shift from a transactional relationship (selling a DVD) to an engagement relationship (monthly subscription) with your customers. Ultimately, this provides an increase in value for you and them.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.economistinsights.com/sites/default/files/EIU_Zuora_WEB_Final.pdf">Subscription options</a> are implemented by 40% of companies and over 80% see subscriptions as having significant growth over the next few years.\r\n\r\n<strong>Benefits of Digital</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Reduced Costs</em>\r\n\r\nThe costs to produce and distribute the content are eliminated. To produce a physical DVD (*not the filming) will cost in the range of $0.75 - $1.00 per DVD, depending on volume. Then, to ship the DVD will cost another $2.00 - $3.00 per DVD.  These costs can be eliminated with digital.\r\n\r\n<em>Reduced Piracy</em>\r\n\r\nPirated copies of DVD’s and printed material cost you in lost revenue, the legal costs of managing it, a devaluation in your brand and more. <a href="http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/zumba-steps-up-efforts-to-combat-counterfeiting-and-piracy-126109723.html">Zumba knows all to well</a> the impact on their business and is working hard to mitigate as much as possible.\r\n\r\n<em>Increase customer engagement</em>\r\n\r\nOnce you sell the DVD the customer’s ability watch the content requires them to have a DVD player nearby. With digital content they can watch anywhere from there mobile device. Increasing the usability allows them to engage with your content more frequently.  Equally, with digital content you can make changes to your content and distribute globally at the push of a button.\r\n\r\nConsumer behaviors and expectations will increasingly demand companies build relationships based transactions rather than individual transactions.\r\n\r\n<strong>Benefits of Subscription</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Increase customer lifetime value</em>\r\n\r\nBy amortizing the cost of acquisition over months or years, the subscription model locks a trusted a relationship you and your customer. From a consumer perspective the model creates incentives for you to create ongoing value with new content.\r\n\r\nFor you it provides a recurring revenue stream that is less prone to annual fluctuation in purchasing behaviors and is more profitable than physical DVD’s. If you sell a physical DVD for $30 and a monthly subscription for $10, by the fourth month of the subscription you have already increased their value by $10.\r\n\r\n<strong>DVD’s on Life Support</strong>\r\n\r\nWhile it’s probably a bit early to say DVD’s are going the way of the VHS tape, the trends continue in that direction. When a customer buys a DVD they get the digital rights to the content.  To satisfy any remaining demand for DVD’s I can imagine using them as an add-on to the purchase of digital rights.\r\n\r\n<em style="color: #4b5c66;">Brian Bettendorf is the Head of Growth for Classcast.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'DVD to Digital Subscription: By the numbers', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'switching-from-dvd-sales-to-a-digital-subscription', '', '', '2014-09-10 03:43:11', '2014-09-10 03:43:11', '', 0, 'http://www.classcast.co/?p=377', 0, 'post', '', 0),
