(394, 2, '2014-09-10 03:37:03', '2014-09-10 03:37:03', '<strong>State of DVD’s vs Digital</strong>\r\n\r\nThe <a href="http://degonline.org" target="_blank">Digital Entertainment Group</a> reports physical disc sales have fallen over 30% since their 2004 peak. While the demand for content is on the rise, more people want content distributed to them through their mobile device.\r\n\r\nShifting to a monthly subscription model for content distribution enables you to shift from a transactional relationship (selling a DVD) to an engagement relationship (monthly subscription) with your customers. Ultimately, this provides an increase in value for you and them.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.economistinsights.com/sites/default/files/EIU_Zuora_WEB_Final.pdf" target="_blank">Subscription options</a> are implemented by 40% of companies and over 80% see subscriptions as having significant growth over the next few years.\r\n\r\n<strong>Benefits of Digital </strong>\r\n\r\nReduced Costs\r\nThe costs to produce and distribute the content are eliminated. To produce a physical DVD (*not the filming) will cost in the range of $0.75 - $1.00 per DVD, depending on volume. Then, to ship the DVD will cost another $2.00 - $3.00 per DVD. These costs can be eliminated with digital.\r\n\r\nReduced Piracy\r\nPirated copies of DVD’s and printed material cost you in lost revenue, the legal costs of managing it, a devaluation in your brand and more. <a href="http://www.economistinsights.com/sites/default/files/EIU_Zuora_WEB_Final.pdf" target="_blank">Zumba knows all to well</a> the impact on their business and is working hard to mitigate as much as possible.\r\n\r\nIncrease customer engagement\r\nOnce you sell the DVD the customer’s ability watch the content requires them to have a DVD player nearby. With digital content they can watch anywhere from there mobile device. Increasing the usability allows them to engage with your content more frequently. Equally, with digital content you can make changes to your content and distribute globally at the push of a button.\r\n\r\nConsumer behaviors and expectations will increasingly demand companies build relationships based transactions rather than individual transactions.\r\n\r\n<strong>Benefits of Subscription</strong>\r\n\r\nIncrease customer lifetime value\r\nBy amortizing the cost of acquisition over months or years, the subscription model locks a trusted a relationship you and your customer. From a consumer perspective the model creates incentives for you to create ongoing value with new content.\r\n\r\nFor you it provides a recurring revenue stream that is less prone to annual fluctuation in purchasing behaviors and is more profitable than physical DVD’s. If you sell a physical DVD for $30 and a monthly subscription for $10, by the fourth month of the subscription you have already increased their value by $10.\r\n\r\n<strong>DVD’s on Life Support</strong>\r\n\r\nWhile it’s probably a bit early to say DVD’s are going the way of the VHS tape, the trends continue in that direction. When a customer buys a DVD they get the digital rights to the content. To satisfy any remaining demand for DVD’s I can imagine using them as an add-on to the purchase of digital rights.', 'Switching from DVD sales to a digital subscription is good for your business', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'switching-dvd-sales-digital-subscription-good-business', '', '', '2014-09-10 03:40:40', '2014-09-10 03:40:40', '', 0, 'http://www.classcast.co/?p=394', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(395, 2, '2014-09-09 00:16:29', '2014-09-09 00:16:29', 'State of DVD’s vs Digital\r\n\r\nThe <a href="http://degonline.org" target="_blank">Digital Entertainment Group</a> reports physical disc sales have fallen over 30% since their 2004 peak. While the demand for content is on the rise, more people want content distributed to them through their mobile device. \r\n\r\nShifting to a monthly subscription model for content distribution enables you to shift from a transactional relationship (selling a DVD) to an engagement relationship (monthly subscription) with your customers. Ultimately, this provides an increase in value for you and them.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.economistinsights.com/sites/default/files/EIU_Zuora_WEB_Final.pdf" target="_blank">Subscription options</a> are implemented by 40% of companies and over 80% see subscriptions as having significant growth over the next few years.\r\n\r\nBenefits of Digital \r\n\r\nReduced Costs\r\nThe costs to produce and distribute the content are eliminated. To produce a physical DVD (*not the filming) will cost in the range of $0.75 - $1.00 per DVD, depending on volume. Then, to ship the DVD will cost another $2.00 - $3.00 per DVD.  These costs can be eliminated with digital.\r\n\r\nReduced Piracy\r\nPirated copies of DVD’s and printed material cost you in lost revenue, the legal costs of managing it, a devaluation in your brand and more. <a href="http://www.economistinsights.com/sites/default/files/EIU_Zuora_WEB_Final.pdf" target="_blank">Zumba knows all to well</a> the impact on their business and is working hard to mitigate as much as possible.\r\n\r\nIncrease customer engagement\r\nOnce you sell the DVD the customer’s ability watch the content requires them to have a DVD player nearby. With digital content they can watch anywhere from there mobile device. Increasing the usability allows them to engage with your content more frequently.  Equally, with digital content you can make changes to your content and distribute globally at the push of a button.\r\n\r\nConsumer behaviors and expectations will increasingly demand companies build relationships based transactions rather than individual transactions.\r\n\r\nBenefits of Subscription\r\n\r\nIncrease customer lifetime value\r\nBy amortizing the cost of acquisition over months or years, the subscription model locks a trusted a relationship you and your customer. From a consumer perspective the model creates incentives for you to create ongoing value with new content. \r\n\r\nFor you it provides a recurring revenue stream that is less prone to annual fluctuation in purchasing behaviors and is more profitable than physical DVD’s. If you sell a physical DVD for $30 and a monthly subscription for $10, by the fourth month of the subscription you have already increased their value by $10.  \r\n\r\nDVD’s on Life Support\r\n\r\nWhile it’s probably a bit early to say DVD’s are going the way of the VHS tape, the trends continue in that direction. When a customer buys a DVD they get the digital rights to the content.  To satisfy any remaining demand for DVD’s I can imagine using them as an add-on to the purchase of digital rights.\r\n', 'Switching from DVD sales to a digital subscription is good for your business', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '394-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-09-09 00:16:29', '2014-09-09 00:16:29', '', 394, 'http://www.classcast.co/394-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(396, 2, '2014-09-09 00:24:03', '2014-09-09 00:24:03', '<strong>State of DVD’s vs Digital</strong>\r\n\r\nThe <a href="http://degonline.org" target="_blank">Digital Entertainment Group</a> reports physical disc sales have fallen over 30% since their 2004 peak. While the demand for content is on the rise, more people want content distributed to them through their mobile device. \r\n\r\nShifting to a monthly subscription model for content distribution enables you to shift from a transactional relationship (selling a DVD) to an engagement relationship (monthly subscription) with your customers. Ultimately, this provides an increase in value for you and them.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.economistinsights.com/sites/default/files/EIU_Zuora_WEB_Final.pdf" target="_blank">Subscription options</a> are implemented by 40% of companies and over 80% see subscriptions as having significant growth over the next few years.\r\n\r\n<strong>Benefits of Digital </strong>\r\n\r\nReduced Costs\r\nThe costs to produce and distribute the content are eliminated. To produce a physical DVD (*not the filming) will cost in the range of $0.75 - $1.00 per DVD, depending on volume. Then, to ship the DVD will cost another $2.00 - $3.00 per DVD.  These costs can be eliminated with digital.\r\n\r\nReduced Piracy\r\nPirated copies of DVD’s and printed material cost you in lost revenue, the legal costs of managing it, a devaluation in your brand and more. <a href="http://www.economistinsights.com/sites/default/files/EIU_Zuora_WEB_Final.pdf" target="_blank">Zumba knows all to well</a> the impact on their business and is working hard to mitigate as much as possible.\r\n\r\nIncrease customer engagement\r\nOnce you sell the DVD the customer’s ability watch the content requires them to have a DVD player nearby. With digital content they can watch anywhere from there mobile device. Increasing the usability allows them to engage with your content more frequently.  Equally, with digital content you can make changes to your content and distribute globally at the push of a button.\r\n\r\nConsumer behaviors and expectations will increasingly demand companies build relationships based transactions rather than individual transactions.\r\n\r\n<strong>Benefits of Subscription</strong>\r\n\r\nIncrease customer lifetime value\r\nBy amortizing the cost of acquisition over months or years, the subscription model locks a trusted a relationship you and your customer. From a consumer perspective the model creates incentives for you to create ongoing value with new content. \r\n\r\nFor you it provides a recurring revenue stream that is less prone to annual fluctuation in purchasing behaviors and is more profitable than physical DVD’s. If you sell a physical DVD for $30 and a monthly subscription for $10, by the fourth month of the subscription you have already increased their value by $10.  \r\n\r\nDVD’s on Life Support\r\n\r\nWhile it’s probably a bit early to say DVD’s are going the way of the VHS tape, the trends continue in that direction. When a customer buys a DVD they get the digital rights to the content.  To satisfy any remaining demand for DVD’s I can imagine using them as an add-on to the purchase of digital rights.\r\n', 'Switching from DVD sales to a digital subscription is good for your business', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '394-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-09-09 00:24:03', '2014-09-09 00:24:03', '', 394, 'http://www.classcast.co/394-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
