nges to your content and distribute globally at the push of a button.\r\n\r\nConsumer behaviors and expectations will increasingly demand companies build relationships based transactions rather than individual transactions.\r\n\r\n<strong>Benefits of Subscription</strong>\r\n\r\n\r\nIncrease customer lifetime value\r\n\r\nBy amortizing the cost of acquisition over months or years, the subscription model locks a trusted a relationship you and your customer. From a consumer perspective the model creates incentives for you to create ongoing value with new content. \r\n\r\nFor you it provides a recurring revenue stream that is less prone to annual fluctuation in purchasing behaviors and is more profitable than physical DVD’s. If you sell a physical DVD for $30 and a monthly subscription for $10, by the fourth month of the subscription you have already increased their value by $10.  \r\n\r\n<strong>DVD’s on Life Support</strong>\r\n\r\nWhile it’s probably a bit early to say DVD’s are going the way of the VHS tape, the trends continue in that direction. When a customer buys a DVD they get the digital rights to the content.  To satisfy any remaining demand for DVD’s I can imagine using them as an add-on to the purchase of digital rights.\r\n', 'Switching from DVD sales to a digital subscription is good for your business', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '394-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-09-09 00:25:34', '2014-09-09 00:25:34', '', 394, 'http://www.classcast.co/394-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
