(411, 2, '2014-10-09 19:48:21', '2014-10-09 19:48:21', 'Launching a new product is hard. Launching a successful new product is even harder. Regardless of your go-to-market plan, your marketing and communications can be the difference between moderate sales and great sales. Let’s face it, you have to have the right product to begin with and a set of customers who wants your product. With our mobile content platform you can be assured we’ve developed and will continue to enhance the platform based on continued customer feedback. It’s up to you to ensure the right type and <a href="https://classcast.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/202967596-What-does-a-good-quality-fitness-video-look-and-sound-like">quality</a> of content is in there. From initial product development through post-product launch, communication with internal teams and customers is critical for product success. This internal and customer communication at each stage of the product needs to be developed with some key attributes in mind.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Who is the message for</li>\r\n	<li>Why should they pay attention to it</li>\r\n	<li>What do you want them to do</li>\r\n	<li>How can they go about doing it</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAlthough this is simple, it doesn’t mean it’s easy. Crafting good messaging is hard and then you need to deliver that message through the right channel. Let’s take a look at few considerations at each phase of the product. <strong>Discovery</strong> <strong>Internal Team Discovery</strong> Getting key stakeholders excited and willing to back the product. Plan for who is going to be the product owner (evangelist), who will manage content production, who will market and support the product. The product owner needs to get each of these people excited and willing to take ownership for their portion of the product, then continue to keep everyone informed about the product and solicit ongoing feedback to evaluate opportunities for improvement. <strong>Customer Discovery</strong> This is all about