(413, 2, '2014-10-09 19:56:03', '2014-10-09 19:56:03', 'Launching a new product is hard. Launching a successful new product is even harder. Regardless of your go-to-market plan, your marketing and communications can be the difference between moderate sales and great sales. Let’s face it, you have to have the right product to begin with and a set of customers who wants your product. With our mobile content platform you can be assured we’ve developed and will continue to enhance the platform based on continued customer feedback. It’s up to you to ensure the right type and <a href="https://classcast.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/202967596-What-does-a-good-quality-fitness-video-look-and-sound-like">quality</a> of content is in there. From initial product development through post-product launch, communication with internal teams and customers is critical for product success. This internal and customer communication at each stage of the product needs to be developed with some key attributes in mind.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Who is the message for</li>\r\n	<li>Why should they pay attention to it</li>\r\n	<li>What do you want them to do</li>\r\n	<li>How can they go about doing it</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAlthough this is simple, it doesn’t mean it’s easy. Crafting good messaging is hard and then you need to deliver that message through the right channel. Let’s take a look at few considerations at each phase of the product. <strong>Discovery</strong> <strong>Internal Team Discovery</strong> Getting key stakeholders excited and willing to back the product. Plan for who is going to be the product owner (evangelist), who will manage content production, who will market and support the product. The product owner needs to get each of these people excited and willing to take ownership for their portion of the product, then continue to keep everyone informed about the product and solicit ongoing feedback to evaluate opportunities for improvement. <strong>Customer Discovery</strong> This is all about learning if your customers want the product, why they would pay for it and their willingness to pay. <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zwh8ThUqeC8">Geoffrey Moore</a> in his book “Crossing the Chasm” describes five phases of technology adoption categorized by the type of buyer:\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Innovators</strong> – Pursue technology for the interest in technology.</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Early adopters</strong> – First to pursue the technology for the intrinsic benefits</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Early majority</strong> – rely on benefits of new technology, but will wait for others to work out the kinks.</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Late majority</strong> – not too interested in technology; waits for a standard to emerge</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Laggards</strong> – don’t want anything to do with technology</p>\r\nAt this phase you want to focus your efforts on the early adopters. These customers will provide your best feedback and also your best advocates. Get out and talk to these people. You probably already know who they are. These are likely your customers who are most engaged with your brand. Ask them for their feedback and show how you’ve listened and incorporated their feedback. You’ll have an army of advocates if they feel they’ve been part of the product solution. Use their feedback to inform copy for your marketing messaging. Following a tested framework for <a href="http://www.custdev.com">customer development</a> can save a lot of time in getting the product right early.\r\n\r\n<strong>Pre-Launch</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Internal Pre-Launch</strong>\r\n\r\nValidate with your team that all assets for launch are ready to go and everyone is familiar with the full product solution and launch plan. This includes the landing page, FAQ’s, Press Release, product video, print and online ads, postcards or one-pagers, support team training, executive/team briefing and more.\r\n\r\n<strong>Customer Pre-Launch</strong>\r\n\r\nReach out the early adopters to let them know what’s coming and that you’d like their support in providing feedback. Consider scheduling a series of video-conferences to provide them the opportunity to learn more details about the product and how they can help.\r\n\r\n<strong>Launch and Beyond</strong> <strong>Internal Launch</strong>\r\n\r\nA lot of work has been completed up this point and its time to keep the traction going. Celebrate your launch and provide regular updates to the team about customer service issues, product feedback, number of trials and other conversion details.\r\n\r\n<strong>Customer Launch</strong>\r\n\r\nWhile your print ads, postcards and other will drive awareness and trial conversions, your efforts to build a two way communication with your early customers and providing them an incentive to accept your will build trust and strengthen your brand. Provide your evangelists/early adopters with suggested messaging to promote through their social channels - remember, these people want to help), design product promotion email to be sent to your customers inviting them to the two weeks free trial - their incentive to try before they buy. Begin capturing testimonials that can be used throughout your messaging to provide social proof on the product. Use a combination of <a href="https://classcast.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/203954193">web based surveys and personal communication</a> to continue gathering feedback about how the product is being used and why the chose to purchase or not purchase.\r\n\r\n<strong>Summary</strong> Effective internal and customer communication is a strong driver of product success. Most importantly, continued feedback from customers is used to drive ongoing product innovation, modifications to the marketing messaging or pricing. Beginning your product journey with effective communication as a key goal will ensure you’ve had the time to refine messaging along the way so when the product finally goes to market you are setting yourself up for success.', 'Communication across the lifecycle for product success', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '407-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-10-09 19:56:03', '2014-10-09 19:56:03', '', 407, 'http://www.classcast.co/407-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
